      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":12,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy — no hard efforts\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first phase is entirely about re-establishing the habit and load tolerance — not fitness. Your physiotherapist has cleared you for 20-minute easy runs only, so every session respects that ceiling. You'll run 3 days per week with at least one rest day between each run. Long run Saturday stays in the plan but is capped at 20 minutes just like the other sessions for now. Walk breaks are built in from day one: start each run with a 3-minute walk, run easy, and if you feel any foot discomfort — even a whisper of it — drop to a walk immediately. No shame in that; it's the smart play. Easy pace is 5:24–5:58 per km. If that still feels too fast, go slower. There is no pace too easy in this phase. Deload in week 4: pull back to the week 1 volume to let tissues consolidate before we build again.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":13,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90/10 easy/moderate — no speed work until physiotherapist clears it\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":350,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":350,\"notes\":\"You've made it through four weeks of consistent, careful running — that's real progress and it came from good decision-making, not luck. In this phase we start extending the Saturday long run beyond 20 minutes, assuming your foot remains symptom-free and you have physiotherapist clearance to increase duration. We'll keep the weekly run count at 3 and let the long run do the heavy lifting. Volume increases no more than 10% week over week. Deload in week 8: reduce to 80% of peak week volume. If foot pain returns at any point, we pause the build and return to Phase 1 volumes — that is not a setback, that is the plan working. Still no tempo, intervals, or repetitions. Your pre-injury fitness (VDOT 46.5) will come back faster than it was built, but only if the foundation is solid.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":19,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":22,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85/15 easy/moderate — tempo introduction only if fully cleared by physiotherapist\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"This phase is conditional — it only proceeds as written if you are fully symptom-free and have explicit physiotherapist clearance for harder efforts. If not, we simply extend the Build phase and that is a completely valid outcome. If cleared, one moderate tempo effort per week may be introduced: a short 10–15 minute segment at around 4:44–4:29 per km (marathon to threshold pace), sandwiched between easy running. The purpose is to remind your neuromuscular system what faster running feels like, not to chase fitness. Three days per week, long run Saturday, and we still protect the foot above all else. Volume peaks conservatively at around 22 km per week — well below your pre-injury capacity, but appropriate given the layoff and injury history.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Taper\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":15,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":15,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"One final week of easy, reduced-volume running to let your body absorb everything from the previous 11 weeks. This is not a week off — it is active recovery and consolidation. Two short easy runs plus one easy long run, all at the gentler end of your easy pace range. Arrive at week 13 feeling fresh, confident, and ready to set a new baseline for what comes next — whether that is a 10K build, continued base development, or whatever goal excites you most.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James, your situation calls for a plan that respects two realities simultaneously: you have a genuine aerobic engine from five years of running and a 44-minute 10K, and you have an active plantar fasciitis injury that is the gatekeeper for everything. The plan is built around that tension. Phase 1 is non-negotiable in its conservatism — plantar fasciitis is notoriously sensitive to load spikes, and the most common mistake in recovery is progressing too fast once pain subsides. The 10% weekly volume cap is applied rigorously throughout. Deload weeks every 3–4 weeks are not optional extras; they are where tissue remodeling and adaptation actually happen. All paces derive from your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5, but easy runs are deliberately placed at the slower end (5:44–5:58 per km) given the injury layoff and the fact that your current fitness is likely below that baseline. Speed work is withheld entirely until physiotherapist clearance — not because you cannot handle it aerobically, but because the plantar fascia is not yet ready for the ground reaction forces of faster running. The 3-days-per-week structure is ideal here: it provides enough stimulus to rebuild while giving the foot genuine recovery time between sessions. Your Saturday long run is honored throughout as your anchor workout. By week 12, the goal is not a race — it is a healthy, confident runner with a rebuilt aerobic base and a foot that is ready for the next chapter.\",\"warnings\":\"IMPORTANT: This plan was designed around your physiotherapist's current clearance for 20-minute easy running only, with no speed work permitted. Before progressing beyond Phase 1 — especially before extending long run duration in Phase 2 or introducing any tempo work in Phase 3 — you must obtain explicit clearance from your physiotherapist. If you experience any return of foot pain during a run, stop and walk immediately; do not attempt to run through it. Persistent or worsening pain should be evaluated by your physiotherapist or a sports medicine physician before you resume running. This plan does not replace medical advice. The paces listed are derived from a pre-injury race result; your current fitness may be lower, and going easier than prescribed is always the right call. Please also note that runner's knee (left) is listed as recovered — continue any physiotherapist-recommended strength or mobility work for that as well, as return-to-running periods can sometimes resurface old issues.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
